      {
         "text": "Regarding the figure of the woman as a goddess, important points from the work of Joseph Campbell must be highlighted (<htcite0>):\n- **Page 314**: The ancestral point of origin of all humanity is related to female figures.\n- **Pages 318 - 320**: Primitive societies possibly had three different types of organization: equal positions between men and women; men predominant with women excluded; and women as supreme figures.\n- **Pages 320 - 321**: Men in societies with female dominance might have been unaware of the process of pregnancy and birth.\n- **Page 325**: Female figures are the first examples of sculpted images, possibly being humanity's first objects of worship.\n\nDespite the existence of these three possible forms of primitive social organization and the fact that the female figure was the first to be worshipped, when we study the political sphere we observe far more men being remembered than women.\n\n#### A Great Exception\n\nThis scenario of restricted political participation in the past ends up creating false impressions about women's capabilities.\n\nNowadays, we observe advances in the field of knowledge that allow us to correct ancient misconceptions. One of these was presented by Dr. Francisco A. González Redondo in one of his lectures, where he demonstrates that women played an important role in the beginnings of mathematics (<htcite1>).\n\nThis process of recognizing equal capabilities is still limited, which is why figures like Wu Zetian (武則天) marked an era (<htcite2>).",
         "source": [
