               "fullname": "Wu Shihuo (武士穫)",
               "sex": "male",
               "gender": "male",
               "is_real": true,
               "haplogroup": null,
               "history": [
                  {
                     "text": "Wu Shihuo (武士穫) was the metropolitan supervisor (都督) of Lizhou (利州)— present-day Guangyuan. This post was granted to him by Emperor Li Shimin (李世民), also known as Taizong (<htcite0>). He is also referred to as a chancellor of the Tang Dynasty (唐代) (<htcite1>). During research, it was not possible to determine whether the positions he held throughout his life were two distinct functions or if the studied sources present discrepancies.\n\nThe discrepancies related to his biography were possibly deepened by Li Jiao (李娇), who, when writing *Panlongtai bei* (攀龍臺碑), may have fabricated elements of the family history (<htcite2>).\n\nHowever, his life is not solely summarized by historiographical discrepancies. One of his acts, as a father, changed the course of history. Unlike many fathers of his time, Wu Shihuo (武士穫) encouraged his daughter to learn to read and write, as well as to develop intellectual skills traditionally reserved for men. Furthermore, he encouraged her to learn music and public speaking (<htcite3>).",
